abstract: A few weeks ago, the London newspapers were didactic and moralizing on the promised (or threatened) visit of LOUIS NAPOLEON to the Queen of England. Suddenly, they have become suspiciously silent on the subject. They eulogize France, they praise the gallantry of French soldiers, but they do not indulge any anticipations of the pleasures and advantages to be gained from an Imperial visit. Perhaps we can throw some little light upon the subject.

abstract: A MISSING GIRL IN CHICAGO.--A singular incident has recently occurred in our city. A servant girl, named JOANNA McCARTY, living in the family of Dr. DAVIS, on State-street, went out on Sunday evening last with a young man who had been in the habit of calling to see her. Since that time nothing whatever has been seen or heard of her.

abstract: Highway Robbery. abstract: A NEW KIND OF DUEL.--The New-Orleans Crescent says that a Frenchman, thinking his honor damaged by another Frenchman's insult, challenged the insulter to fight. The challenged having the choice of weapons, and standing in wholesome dread of "bullets and blades," as Bob Acres says, chose hoop-poles. course the fight came off with the selected tools, and the wounded honor of each was healed by having his body, head and shoulders badly bruised.

abstract: The steamship Northern Light arrived here today, with dates from San Francisco to the 23d of December, and with about $600,000 in specie for New-York. abstract: Leghorn--an uncouth corruption of Livorne, its musical Italian name-is not only the chief sea-port of Tuscany, but it is one of the most important in the Mediterranean. It lies in a low plain, which spreads outward for several miles, and behind which the Appenines rise in successful ridges, distinctly visible as you approach the town, and girding the whole eastern and southern horizon.

abstract: It is the manifest destiny of this age to get the news. Cut the Telegraph wire and it will take to pigeon's wings. abstract: Another failure yesterday. I perceive, in the mail from this City to New-York, as no Washington letters o Tuesday night appear in the papers of to-day. What can be the cause of this ? Can it be the fogs on the bay, which prevent the boat getting up from Amboy ? If so, why cannot some arrangement be made to send the newspaper letters front Philadelphia to New-York by the late railroad train !

abstract: In the Missouri Legislature, on the 11th inst., the balloting for United States Senator was resumed. abstract: SHAKSPEARE IN RUSSIA.-There are translations of some of SHAKSPEARE'S plays performed in Russia. The most frequently witnessed are "Hamlet" and " King Lear:" the class of shopkeepers, who may be called the people in Russia, for the others are mere serfs, are those by whom they are chiefly appreciated, and SHAKSPEARE is reverenced by most of them nearly as much as in England, although they have read his works only in a translation.

abstract: Minnesota is a great country, not merely in extent, (though four times the size of Ohio,) but in all that belongs to it,-climate, soil, scenery, productions, and inhabitants. abstract: Within a few days the character of our Autumn and Winter weather has changed for the better. Rain has been falling, not abundantly indeed, but enough to revive hope, since the daily report from the rivers is "rising." To planters and merchants no news could be more agreeable. In many localities the wells were failing, and had the drouth continued a few weeks longer, much suffering must have been the result.

abstract: THE LATE GALE AT ROCKLAND, ME.--The loss by the gale and high tide at Rockland on the 19th is estimated at $20,000. The damage to the lime sheds, wharves and kilns of D. C. HASKELL, W. C.  T. B. McINTOSH, M. E. THURLO, and C. MORRILL, is set down at 83,500. Their wharves were partly carried away. The wharf of Messrs. FARWELL  CROCKETT was swept away.

abstract: Brooklyn Tract Society. The Twenty-fifth Anniversary of the Brooklyn City Tract Society was held last evening in the Second Presbyterian Church in that city. Rev.
